<p><b>Edward Paul Abbey</b> (January 29, 1927 – March 14, 1989) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> author and essayist noted for his advocacy of <a href="/wiki/Natural_environment" title="Natural environment">environmental</a> issues and criticism of <a href="/wiki/Public_land" title="Public land">public land</a> policies. His best-known works include the novel <i><a href="/wiki/The_Monkey_Wrench_Gang" title="The Monkey Wrench Gang">The Monkey Wrench Gang</a></i>, which has been cited as an inspiration by radical environmental groups, and the non-fiction work <i><a href="/wiki/Desert_Solitaire" title="Desert Solitaire">Desert Solitaire</a></i>. Writer <a href="/wiki/Larry_McMurtry" title="Larry McMurtry">Larry McMurtry</a> referred to Abbey as the "<a href="/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau" title="Henry David Thoreau">Thoreau</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Western_United_States" title="Western United States">American West</a>".</p>
